<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Wentzel, Willard Ferdinand. A Continuation of the Journal of the Forks Mackenzie's River for Summer 1807-1808. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0022</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p></p>
<p class="head">May Cont<sup>d</sup> 1808</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">This is some imagin'd vision again of theirs which however rediculous &amp; probably without foundation, keeps the Indians in a continual alarm &amp; thus prevents them from working had I had men to send with them these frivolous fears would perhaps <span class="AddHand-author">have</span> been lulled into safety, by the great confidence they put in having a Canadian with them &#8211; it is then in their opinion impossible for them to be in danger<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Here again my last resource is blasted<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  What returns will I have this year<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Curse that timidity of theirs<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Sun<sup>y</sup> 16<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Early in the morning as the sun was about 2½ Hours high we <span class="DelHand-author">a</span><span class="AddHand-author">w</span>ere all surprized at the Circles &amp; demicles circumfering the whole atmosphere<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Coulours were red, yellow, &amp; purple with white Stripes here &amp; there<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[I]</span>ts Form run thus &#8211; <span class="AddHand-editors">[Diagram]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="AddHand-editors">[I]</span>t is very remarkable that the moon tho' in its last quarter Should here appear as bright as at midnight<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>his lasted about 2½ hours again &amp; then took another form a different from this<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  It had however no visible effect upon the weather which was very warm &amp; Clear<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Ice of the Grand River came down from above &#8211; in very large quantities<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">M<sup>y</sup> 17<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Genereux arranging a P<sup>r</sup> of Ballances<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Grand River <span class="DelHand-author">dri<span class="AddHand-author">v</span>ng</span> driving Ice<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[A]</span>n Indian came to day with 6 B<sup>rs</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  F.W. &amp; Rangé foun<span class="AddHand-editors">[d]</span> two dead B<sup>rs</sup> on the other side of the Grand River to day<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Tues<sup>y</sup> 18<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Wednes<sup>y</sup> 19<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Sent the Indian who arrived the day before yesterd<sup>y</sup> in quest of Jollibois<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The men preparing w<span class="DelHand-author">e</span><span class="AddHand-author">ed</span>ges &amp; mallets to press the packs<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[R]</span>ained &amp; snowed yester<sup>y</sup> all day<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[L]</span>ast night we had pretty Smart Frost<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Thurs<sup>y</sup> 20<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Got 6 Packs made<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Snowed, rained &amp; blowed all day ve<span class="AddHand-author">r</span>y cold weather<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[35]</span></p>

